==Quick facts==
[[File:PetcoPark.jpg|thumb|[[PETCO Park]], home of the San Diego Padres (2004<U+2013>present)]]
[[File:PetcoBallParkByPhilKonstantin.jpg|thumb|[[PETCO Park]], as seen from overhead]]

:'''Founded:''' 1969 ([[National League]] expansion)
:'''Current uniform colors:''' [[Dark blue (color)|Dark blue]], [[Sand (color)|Sand]], and [[White]]
:'''Logo design:''' White interlocking 'S' and 'D'
:'''[[DHL Hometown Heroes|Hometown Hero]]:''' [[Tony Gwynn]]
:'''Nicknames:''' The Friars, the "Pads" (pronounced as "Pods")
:'''Most winning season:''' (1998) 98<U+2013>64. Western Division Title and National League Pennant Winners.
:'''Most losing season:''' (1969) 52<U+2013>110
:'''Local television:''' Channel 4 San Diego ([[4SD]]) (Cable TV only; not available over the air.)
:'''TV announcers:''' [[Dick Enberg]], [[Mark Grant]], [[Tony Gwynn]] (occasionally), [[Mark Neely]] (substitute).
:'''Local radio:''' 1090 AM [[XEPRS-AM|XX 1090 (pronounced "Double X")]], [[XEMO-AM|La Poderosa 860 AM (en espa<U+00F1>ol)]].
:'''Radio announcers:''' [[Ted Leitner]], [[Andy Masur]], [[Jerry Coleman]] (home day games).
:'''Spring training facility:''' [[Peoria Sports Complex]], [[Peoria, AZ]]
:'''Rivals:''' [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] (Division), [[Colorado Rockies]] (Division), [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] (Division, geographical), [[San Francisco Giants]] (Division), [[St. Louis Cardinals]] (Post-Season), [[Seattle Mariners]] (Inter-league)

